. * PART 2: HYPOTHESIS TESTING FOR OLS ASSUMPTIONS

* 1. Heteroskedasticity (Breusch-Pagan) 

 * H0: Homoskedasticity (Constant Variance). If Prob > chi2 < 0.05, reject H0.
 
. estat hettest

Breusch–Pagan/Cook–Weisberg test for heteroskedasticity 
Assumption: Normal error terms
Variable: Fitted values of averageprice

H0: Constant variance

    chi2(1) = 1638.23
Prob > chi2 =  0.0000

* 2. Multicollinearity (VIF)

* Rule of thumb: If Mean VIF > 5 or individual VIF > 10, variables are too correlated.


. estat vif

    Variable |       VIF       1/VIF  
-------------+----------------------
 totalvolume |      1.06    0.945565
2.type_num~c |      1.06    0.945952
        year |
       2016  |      1.38    0.722151
       2017  |      1.39    0.721447
       2018  |      1.14    0.874218
-------------+----------------------
    Mean VIF |      1.21


* 3. Panel Autocorrelation (Wooldridge Test) 

* Set panel structure before running panel-specific time series tests

. egen panel_id = group(region_numeric type_numeric)

. xtset panel_id date_clean, delta(7 days)

Panel variable: panel_id (unbalanced)
 Time variable: date_clean, 04jan2015 to 25mar2018, but with gaps
         Delta: 7 days


. * PART 3: ROBUST FINAL MODEL (CORRECTING VIOLATIONS)

FINAL MODEL: Clustered OLS Regression
. 
. * This model uses cluster-robust standard errors to fix both heteroskedasticity and 
serial correlation violations found during your hypothesis tests.

. regress averageprice totalvolume i.type_numeric i.year, vce(cluster region_numeric)

